Higher winds out of the southeast today are testing the western boundary of the Sunday Afternoon Fire in Everglades National Park. To read the full news release, visit: https://www.nps.gov/ever/learn/news/patrolling-sunday-afternoon-fire-perimeter-under-high-winds.htm NPS Photo by Josh Pargas
Learn more about Mission 66 at Everglades National Park here: https://www.nps.gov/subjects/southfloridacollections/mission-66.htm #ThrowbackThursday #NationalParkWeek

Today, the tower is one of the most visited destinations in Everglades National Park, providing visitors with inspiring, panoramic views of the River of Grass. Does this tower look familiar to you? You can find a tower similar to ours in another park! Can you guess which one?

To address this, Mission 66 was launched in 1956. With its large slabs of concrete, swirling ramp, flat roof, and terraces supported by thin columns, the Shark Valley Observation Tower is a classic expression of the modern architectural style that defined the Mission 66 era.

After World War II, the development of the highway system and the rise of automobile culture led Americans to visit national parks in unprecedented numbers. The increased visitation, combined with a lack of funding, resulted in significant wear and tear on park facilities.

The Shark Valley Observation Tower, completed in 1964, was one of several projects in @EvergladesNPS that arose from Mission 66—a 10-year program intended to modernize national parks by 1966, in time for the 50th anniversary of the @NatlParkService. NPS Photo by Daniel Miguel

News Release – With lighter winds out of the north today, fire crews continued to make significant progress on containing the Sunday Afternoon Fire in Everglades National Park. The full news release is available here: https://www.nps.gov/ever/learn/news/everglades-fire-crews-receive-assistance-from-south-florida-water-management-district.htm NPS Photo by Reggie Bray

Happy #EarthDay! 2020 marks the 50th anniversary of Earth Day, a day established to bring awareness to environmental issues and encourage stewardship of our planet's natural resources. Take a moment today to appreciate our amazing planet! Photo by Devin Belliston
The cause of the fire remains under investigation. Future updates will be available on our social media channels and our website at:

As a reminder, South Florida is currently experiencing hot, dry conditions typical of this time of year. Everyone can help prevent wildfires by fully extinguishing cigarettes, reporting smoke and fire immediately, and carefully monitoring and fully extinguishing outdoor fires.

Personnel from Big Cypress National Preserve, Alaska Fire Service, Florida Forest Service, South Florida Water Management District, Great Smoky Mountains National Park and aviation resources from the Silver King Fire at Big Cypress National Preserve are assisting.

Surrounding communities in Miami-Dade and Broward counties may continue to experience smoke from the wildfire. Drivers should use caution when smoke is on the road. Individuals with respiratory conditions should stay indoors when smoke is present.

The majority of the fire activity on April 20 occurred along the north, west and south sides of the fire. Firefighters are using both aerial and ground resources to conduct direct attack and burn out operations to contain and slow the fire’s spread.
A reconnaissance flight more accurately mapped the fire today at just under 1,300 acres. The fire is 20% contained in the park, up from 10% yesterday, and the state’s portion is 80% contained.
With the current hot, dry conditions, firefighters are aggressively working to suppress the fire and reduce the impact on surrounding communities. NPS Photo
